00:02:02.190 --> 00:02:03.490
&gt;&gt; Howard Ross: Hi, everybody.

00:02:03.490 --> 00:02:04.790
Good afternoon.

00:02:04.790 --> 00:02:11.540
I'm going to actually start
with a little video clip.

00:02:11.540 --> 00:02:13.010 position:56%
&gt;&gt; [Background Music] He's the boss.

00:02:13.010 --> 00:02:15.560
She's bossy -- the negative way.

00:02:15.560 --> 00:02:18.270
Women are perceived at
the office in a new ad

00:02:18.270 --> 00:02:23.310
for Pantene that's gone viral.

00:02:23.310 --> 00:02:26.430
It's hit a nerve so we
set out to find the truth.

00:02:26.430 --> 00:02:30.380
Are women who act exactly the
same as men seen differently?

00:02:30.380 --> 00:02:31.960
Listen to this woman.

00:02:31.960 --> 00:02:34.710
How do you feel about
her as a job candidate?

00:02:34.710 --> 00:02:37.550
&gt;&gt; I know the Windows operating
systems like the back of my hand.

00:02:37.550 --> 00:02:38.850
No problem.

00:02:38.850 --> 00:02:40.150
&gt;&gt; Now, listen to him.

00:02:40.150 --> 00:02:42.370
&gt;&gt; I know the Windows operating
systems like the back of my hand.

00:02:42.370 --> 00:02:43.670
No problem.

00:02:43.670 --> 00:02:45.380
&gt;&gt; The candidates in
these videos are actors

00:02:45.380 --> 00:02:48.130
in a Yale University
hiring experiment.

00:02:48.130 --> 00:02:51.980
The resumes identical,
the interviews identical.

00:02:51.980 --> 00:02:54.740
&gt;&gt; I'm extremely good at
sizing up people quickly

00:02:54.740 --> 00:02:56.780
and delegating responsibility
accordingly.

00:02:56.780 --> 00:03:01.240 position:56%
&gt;&gt; The only difference is gender but
when it comes to who got the job?

00:03:01.240 --> 00:03:04.360
&gt;&gt; I thought the male applicant
had better soft skills.

00:03:04.360 --> 00:03:07.910
I'd say the woman was
arrogant and over-selling.

00:03:07.910 --> 00:03:11.740
&gt;&gt; In hundreds of evaluations,
the female job seekers come off

00:03:11.740 --> 00:03:14.730
as more aggressive,
are rated less likeable

00:03:14.730 --> 00:03:16.650 position:56%
and they're less likely to be hired.

00:03:16.650 --> 00:03:18.060
&gt;&gt; Isn't it a Catch 22?

00:03:18.060 --> 00:03:19.930
You're supposed to be
strong to get that job.

00:03:19.930 --> 00:03:22.150
And you're saying if you're
too strong, you won't get it.

00:03:22.150 --> 00:03:25.170
&gt;&gt; You need to behave in
this dominant way to advance

00:03:25.170 --> 00:03:26.690
as a woman in the workplace.

00:03:26.690 --> 00:03:27.990
But you're seen negatively

00:03:27.990 --> 00:03:30.160
because that's not how we
expect women to behave.

00:03:30.160 --> 00:03:34.380
&gt;&gt; And if you think this is
just male bias, it's not.

00:03:34.380 --> 00:03:38.200
Both men and women doing the
hiring made the same call.

00:03:38.200 --> 00:03:40.660
&gt;&gt; I think there's a level
of arrogance that becomes --

00:03:40.660 --> 00:03:43.380
that might be okay to be a manager
but then there's a step above

00:03:43.380 --> 00:03:44.830
and I thought she was
slightly above that.

00:03:44.830 --> 00:03:48.080
&gt;&gt; So let's talk and when we
revealed our study results --

00:03:48.080 --> 00:03:50.600
&gt;&gt; I was surprised by my reaction.

00:03:50.600 --> 00:03:53.560
&gt;&gt; What does that say about us?

00:03:53.560 --> 00:03:55.970
&gt;&gt; We've a long way to go.

00:03:58.040 --> 00:03:59.480
&gt;&gt; Howard Ross: Yeah, we do
have a long way to go, don't we?

00:03:59.480 --> 00:04:02.460
We don't have to go far from the
morning's news each day to see

00:04:02.460 --> 00:04:04.100 position:56%
that we still have a long way to go.

00:04:04.100 --> 00:04:06.220
And you know, we look at
circumstances like this

00:04:06.220 --> 00:04:07.810
and of course, the first
question that comes

00:04:07.810 --> 00:04:10.630
to mind is a question
of equity and justice.

00:04:10.630 --> 00:04:12.290
You know, how can people
be successful

00:04:12.290 --> 00:04:14.900
if they're not treated fairly
simply because of gender or race

00:04:14.900 --> 00:04:16.630
or any other distinction?

00:04:16.630 --> 00:04:18.170
And there's another -- excuse me --

00:04:18.170 --> 00:04:21.010
another important question
too which is how are we going

00:04:21.010 --> 00:04:23.960
to possibly make decent
talent management choices

00:04:23.960 --> 00:04:27.900 position:56%
if we're making them based on things
we don't even know are manipulating

00:04:27.900 --> 00:04:29.250
our minds?

00:04:29.250 --> 00:04:31.880
And so I want to start this
afternoon by saying, you know,

00:04:31.880 --> 00:04:33.590
"I don't care what
your politics are."

00:04:33.590 --> 00:04:35.650
You know, I don't care whether
you're a Democrat or a Republican.

00:04:35.650 --> 00:04:37.100
I don't care whether
you see yourselves

00:04:37.100 --> 00:04:38.770
as liberal or conservative.

00:04:38.770 --> 00:04:40.630
And that's something
we might talk over --

00:04:40.630 --> 00:04:43.530 position:56%
talk about over lunch although these
days, people are afraid to talk

00:04:43.530 --> 00:04:45.350
about those things over lunch.

00:04:45.350 --> 00:04:48.700
What I want to talk about
is how does this dynamic,

00:04:48.700 --> 00:04:51.460
this unconscious way
we make decisions

00:04:51.460 --> 00:04:55.110
about people impact the essence
of who we are as human beings,

00:04:55.110 --> 00:04:58.090
at our jobs, at work,
on the streets?

00:04:58.090 --> 00:05:01.130
How does it impact people's
lives, their livelihoods?

00:05:01.130 --> 00:05:04.430
And it's not, we know because
most people wake up in the morning

00:05:04.430 --> 00:05:06.560
and say, "Hmm, how can I
suppress the people of color

00:05:06.560 --> 00:05:08.430
in my organization today?"

00:05:08.430 --> 00:05:11.130
How can I hold down
the women, you know?

00:05:11.130 --> 00:05:12.710
I'm not saying there aren't
some people like that.

00:05:12.710 --> 00:05:15.320
Of course, we know there's some
but overwhelmingly the issue

00:05:15.320 --> 00:05:17.770
that we deal with especially
in organizations like yours,

00:05:17.770 --> 00:05:21.320 position:56%
especially in organizations where
we have a relatively highly educated

00:05:21.320 --> 00:05:23.940
workforce and, you know, people
who are committed to be a part

00:05:23.940 --> 00:05:27.460
of a larger organization --
it rarely shows up that way.

00:05:27.460 --> 00:05:30.490 position:56%
Something else is going on and it's
something that if we tell the truth,

00:05:30.490 --> 00:05:32.530
each of us has experienced.

00:05:32.530 --> 00:05:35.930
I remember I was down
-- two years ago,

00:05:35.930 --> 00:05:38.730
I was down at the Jackson
State University in Jackson,

00:05:38.730 --> 00:05:41.180
Mississippi doing some work for
a couple of days with the deans

00:05:41.180 --> 00:05:43.950
and the faculty members down there.

00:05:43.950 --> 00:05:46.590
And I had to fly from there to
New York City for another client

00:05:46.590 --> 00:05:48.050
so I had to go through
Memphis, Tennessee.

00:05:48.050 --> 00:05:51.230
And I got to Memphis in
time for my last flight out.

00:05:51.230 --> 00:05:54.830
And as soon as I get through the
gate, the gate attendant comes on

00:05:54.830 --> 00:05:57.890
and says, "Ladies and gentlemen,
there'll be a 45-minute delay."

00:05:57.890 --> 00:06:00.890
And the words were barely out of
her mouth when this voice boos

00:06:00.890 --> 00:06:03.470
out from behind, "You
talking to us, lady?"

00:06:03.470 --> 00:06:05.330
And I turned around and
there's a guy sitting behind me

00:06:05.330 --> 00:06:08.460
who I would best describe as
Santa Claus with an attitude.

00:06:08.460 --> 00:06:11.670
Older white guy, big white beard,
white hair, wearing overalls

00:06:11.670 --> 00:06:14.660
and a flannel shirt with a
car magazine in his hand.

00:06:14.660 --> 00:06:16.540
Yeah, you're chuckling
like I did, you know.

00:06:16.540 --> 00:06:18.190
I kind of got him pegged, right?

00:06:18.190 --> 00:06:20.020
So I went about my
business on my computer

00:06:20.020 --> 00:06:21.480
until it was time to
get on the plane.

00:06:21.480 --> 00:06:22.780
It comes time to get on the plane.

00:06:22.780 --> 00:06:25.710
I get down to my seat and lo and
behold, who's sitting next to me

00:06:25.710 --> 00:06:27.010
but angry Santa Claus [laughter].

00:06:27.010 --> 00:06:28.310
&gt;&gt; Oh yeah.

00:06:28.310 --> 00:06:29.690
&gt;&gt; Howard Ross: So we did the nod.

00:06:29.690 --> 00:06:30.990
Travelers know what I mean.

00:06:30.990 --> 00:06:32.920
You know and you kind of sit down.

00:06:32.920 --> 00:06:34.850
We take off, go into
parallel plane mode.

00:06:34.850 --> 00:06:36.150
I'm working on my computer.

00:06:36.150 --> 00:06:38.280
He's reading his magazine.

00:06:38.280 --> 00:06:42.200
We fly for a couple of hours until
it's time to do the initial descent

00:06:42.200 --> 00:06:44.460
to New York City so
I closed my computer.

00:06:44.460 --> 00:06:46.630
And travelers know this is
when airplane chat starts

00:06:46.630 --> 00:06:48.710
because it's now safe to talk
to the person next to you.

00:06:48.710 --> 00:06:50.670
You're not going to get stuck
in a two-hour conversation

00:06:50.670 --> 00:06:53.190 position:56%
with a lunatic, you know [laughter].

00:06:53.190 --> 00:06:55.900
And so I turned to him and I say,
"So what takes you to New York?"

00:06:55.900 --> 00:06:57.270
And he says, "I've got
a business meeting."

00:06:57.270 --> 00:06:58.570
I said, "Really, what
are you doing?"

00:06:58.570 --> 00:07:00.700
And he says, "I'm a radiologist."

00:07:00.700 --> 00:07:03.350
So boom! There goes
that picture, you know.

00:07:03.350 --> 00:07:05.840
So now, I was sort of nonplussed
and a little embarrassed.

00:07:05.840 --> 00:07:07.620
And I said, "So what
kind of radiology?"

00:07:07.620 --> 00:07:09.040
And he says, "Well, you
might be interested in this,"

00:07:09.040 --> 00:07:11.020
because I was working on a deck
that I was going to be using

00:07:11.020 --> 00:07:13.680
and he had clearly been, you
know, kind of catching glimpses.

00:07:13.680 --> 00:07:14.980
He said, "We're studying the brain.

00:07:14.980 --> 00:07:17.950
We're watching it on a functional
magnetic resonating image array

00:07:17.950 --> 00:07:21.290
and we can actually determine
which parts of the brain responds

00:07:21.290 --> 00:07:24.680
when people interact with
different kinds of people.

00:07:24.680 --> 00:07:27.150
Yeah, exactly so he's studying the
very thing I'm the most interested

00:07:27.150 --> 00:07:28.450
in [laughter].

00:07:28.450 --> 00:07:31.370
And had I not pegged him as angry
Santa the car mechanic and talked

00:07:31.370 --> 00:07:32.670
to him a little bit earlier,

00:07:32.670 --> 00:07:34.120
I probably would have saved
myself months of research

00:07:34.120 --> 00:07:35.780
on my book, so [laughter].

00:07:35.780 --> 00:07:39.070
So I say that because I'm
not here to talk about you.

00:07:39.070 --> 00:07:42.390
This is who we are as human
beings, every single one of us.

00:07:42.390 --> 00:07:45.030
Now we each have different
aspects that we respond to,

00:07:45.030 --> 00:07:47.430
different kinds of
people we respond to.

00:07:47.430 --> 00:07:50.190
But this is fundamental to
who we are as human beings.

00:07:50.190 --> 00:07:52.730
And it's important for us to
recognize that because if we look

00:07:52.730 --> 00:07:55.080
at the background through
which we've seen diversity

00:07:55.080 --> 00:07:58.060
and inclusion work over a
period of time, it really comes

00:07:58.060 --> 00:07:59.360
from a very different angle.

00:07:59.360 --> 00:08:01.680
I've been paid for doing this
work now for over 30 years.

00:08:01.680 --> 00:08:04.100
I go back to the times some
of you remember when the kind

00:08:04.100 --> 00:08:06.390
of diversity workshops we did
were with the two-by-four.

00:08:06.390 --> 00:08:08.140
You know, you kind of beat
people over the head especially

00:08:08.140 --> 00:08:10.660
if they look like this until at
some point they saw the error

00:08:10.660 --> 00:08:11.960
of their ways.

00:08:11.960 --> 00:08:13.650
It was always very cathartic
if they cried [laughter].

00:08:13.650 --> 00:08:18.010
And then -- and then -- and then
people would sort of you know,

00:08:18.010 --> 00:08:19.340 position:56%
see the light and you would believe.

00:08:19.340 --> 00:08:20.990
But what I began to
notice was when we talked

00:08:20.990 --> 00:08:24.970 position:56%
to those people a month later or two
months later, more times than not,

00:08:24.970 --> 00:08:26.270
they would say, "Well,
that was fine.

00:08:26.270 --> 00:08:27.570
Just don't make me
ever do it again."

00:08:27.570 --> 00:08:31.280
It was a recipe for getting people
to watch out what not to do,

00:08:31.280 --> 00:08:35.070
to be careful what not to say but
it wasn't a recipe for inclusion.

00:08:35.070 --> 00:08:37.230
It wasn't a recipe
for truly engaging,

00:08:37.230 --> 00:08:38.530
getting people to truly engage.

00:08:38.530 --> 00:08:40.730
In fact, sometimes, it
had the opposite effect.

00:08:40.730 --> 00:08:42.970
They had people be
even more tentative.

00:08:42.970 --> 00:08:44.270
You talk about race.

00:08:44.270 --> 00:08:45.570
I'm heading out of here because I
don't want to say the wrong thing

00:08:45.570 --> 00:08:46.980
and get in trouble again.

00:08:46.980 --> 00:08:51.360
So if we look at that, we can kind
of see that there is a paradigm

00:08:51.360 --> 00:08:55.110 position:56%
that we dealt with these issues of
diversity with for a long, long time

00:08:55.110 --> 00:08:58.510
and it's this one -- this sort
of us versus them paradigm.

00:08:58.510 --> 00:09:01.330
And as soon as an issue comes
up, we immediately put ourselves

00:09:01.330 --> 00:09:04.010
into a particular position
that we've already established.

00:09:04.010 --> 00:09:06.350
So if you think about something
like I know many people --

00:09:06.350 --> 00:09:09.670
how many people remember
the incident that happened

00:09:09.670 --> 00:09:12.240
with Skip Gates -- with the
Harvard history professor?

00:09:12.240 --> 00:09:13.540
You remember the Beer Summit?

00:09:13.540 --> 00:09:15.150
Right, so Professor Gates,

00:09:15.150 --> 00:09:18.370 position:56%
one of America's most notable
historians -- he's African-American.

00:09:18.370 --> 00:09:20.200
He comes home from a trip to Asia.

00:09:20.200 --> 00:09:22.960
He comes to his front door
in Cambridge, Massachusetts.

00:09:22.960 --> 00:09:25.000
He's locked out so he breaks
a window so he can get in.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:26.300
Police officers show up.

00:09:26.300 --> 00:09:28.120 position:56%
Something happens and he's arrested.

00:09:28.120 --> 00:09:30.630
It becomes big -- you
know, big news.

00:09:30.630 --> 00:09:32.300
The next morning, there's
his picture

00:09:32.300 --> 00:09:34.310 position:56%
of his mug shot on the morning news.

00:09:34.310 --> 00:09:39.000
How many of us when we heard that
story already knew what happened?

00:09:39.000 --> 00:09:40.300
You see what I mean?

00:09:40.300 --> 00:09:41.660
Either we knew that
it was one more time

00:09:41.660 --> 00:09:44.430
when it was a white police officer
treating an African-American

00:09:44.430 --> 00:09:47.410
in a particular way or we knew,
if we were on the other side

00:09:47.410 --> 00:09:49.010
of equation, one more time

00:09:49.010 --> 00:09:51.810
when a public servant just
doing his job is called a racist

00:09:51.810 --> 00:09:53.110
for no reason.

00:09:53.110 --> 00:09:54.950
Whatever it is, we choose
sides and this is the nature

00:09:54.950 --> 00:09:56.620
of this us-versus-them dynamic.

00:09:56.620 --> 00:09:58.920
If you have any question
about this, by the way,

00:09:58.920 --> 00:10:02.160
read the news this morning about
the president's speech last night.

00:10:02.160 --> 00:10:06.470
Or better yet, watch MSNBC and
Fox News and you will wonder

00:10:06.470 --> 00:10:09.580
if you were watching the
same speech [laughter].

00:10:09.580 --> 00:10:13.770 position:56%
Because most of the responses -- and
we have to acknowledge on all sides,

00:10:13.770 --> 00:10:16.540
most of the responses we
were already ready for.

00:10:16.540 --> 00:10:18.390 position:56%
Those of us who, like the president,

00:10:18.390 --> 00:10:19.940
were ready to agree
with what he said.

00:10:19.940 --> 00:10:21.780
Those of us who don't like
the president were ready

00:10:21.780 --> 00:10:25.590
to have all the excuses because we
no longer look at issues and think

00:10:25.590 --> 00:10:27.690
about the issues that
come to determinations.

00:10:27.690 --> 00:10:30.450
We come from our ideology
to those issues looking

00:10:30.450 --> 00:10:32.300
for how we can be right.

00:10:32.300 --> 00:10:35.450
And if we're going to move forward
with this issue, we need to be able

00:10:35.450 --> 00:10:38.290
to look at the whole
dynamic that's here --

00:10:38.290 --> 00:10:41.140
because what gets produced is what
I call a conversational network

00:10:41.140 --> 00:10:42.440
of contention.

00:10:42.440 --> 00:10:45.960
So this tension that we have
around talking about these issues

00:10:45.960 --> 00:10:48.720
that makes it so painful and
frankly, for a lot of people,

00:10:48.720 --> 00:10:50.950
so frightening to talk
about the issues.

00:10:50.950 --> 00:10:53.480
And that's the background to which
we've historically done diversity

00:10:53.480 --> 00:10:55.160
and inclusion work.

00:10:55.160 --> 00:10:59.280
So when we look at it over a period
of time, we go back 30 to 40 years

00:10:59.280 --> 00:11:02.670
when we -- when this movement
really took on in organizations --

00:11:02.670 --> 00:11:07.500
mostly we were looking at coming
