00:43:33.160 --> 00:43:35.420
The notion is that you can't teach
an old dog new tricks isn't even

00:43:35.420 --> 00:43:36.720
true for dogs.

00:43:36.720 --> 00:43:39.160
We're always learning new things.

00:43:39.160 --> 00:43:42.560
I remember when my
stepfather who passed away

00:43:42.560 --> 00:43:44.260
about a year-and-a-half ago now.

00:43:44.260 --> 00:43:47.560
He was 83 when he learned
to use the internet.

00:43:47.560 --> 00:43:50.600
And it was life altering for
him because now he could shop

00:43:50.600 --> 00:43:54.090
for himself even though, you know,
he couldn't drive himself anymore.

00:43:54.090 --> 00:43:57.400
He could send notes to
people and receive them.

00:43:57.400 --> 00:44:00.900
I even taught him to Skype
so that he could, you know,

00:44:00.900 --> 00:44:02.290
we could talk to him face-to-face.

00:44:02.290 --> 00:44:05.270
It was life altering and at 83
years old, he learned to do it.

00:44:05.270 --> 00:44:07.420
But he wasn't a techno
-- a technical guy.

00:44:07.420 --> 00:44:10.790
It's just that you know, we
learn new things all the time.

00:44:10.790 --> 00:44:14.130
So six ways -- the first is
by far, the most important.

00:44:14.130 --> 00:44:16.440
And that is to recognize and
accept that we have bias.

00:44:16.440 --> 00:44:18.420
That it's foundational to
have it as we see the world.

00:44:18.420 --> 00:44:19.920 position:56%
The question is not do we have bias?

00:44:19.920 --> 00:44:21.630
The question is which are ours?

00:44:21.630 --> 00:44:23.290
And every single person
in this room,

00:44:23.290 --> 00:44:25.110
if you tell the truth, knows this.

00:44:25.110 --> 00:44:26.930
We know that there are
certain people who are inclined

00:44:26.930 --> 00:44:28.230
to like more than others.

00:44:28.230 --> 00:44:30.450
We know that we go into that
party where there's nobody there

00:44:30.450 --> 00:44:32.680
who we know and we make
a quick mental decision

00:44:32.680 --> 00:44:34.480
as to who's the person we're
going to go up to talk to --

00:44:34.480 --> 00:44:37.010
based on who looks
safer or more welcoming.

00:44:37.010 --> 00:44:38.310
Based on what?

00:44:38.310 --> 00:44:41.150
Who has looked safer, more
welcoming like that before?

00:44:41.150 --> 00:44:43.260
We project onto that
circumstance what we've learned

00:44:43.260 --> 00:44:45.410
in the past from our book of rules.

00:44:45.410 --> 00:44:48.490 position:56%
And the metaphor I like to use for
this is it's kind of like the clutch

00:44:48.490 --> 00:44:51.370
in a standard transmission
automobile for those of you

00:44:51.370 --> 00:44:53.850
who even remember standard
transmission automobiles.

00:44:53.850 --> 00:44:56.760
When you step on the clutch,
the motor doesn't stop running.

00:44:56.760 --> 00:44:58.060
The motor is still running.

00:44:58.060 --> 00:45:00.430
It just disengaged
from running the car.

00:45:00.430 --> 00:45:03.900
Similarly if I say to myself,
"Okay, I have a bias about this.

00:45:03.900 --> 00:45:06.140
I better be careful about this."

00:45:06.140 --> 00:45:08.340
When I've been talking or
interacting with that person,

00:45:08.340 --> 00:45:09.640
I have a chance to separate.

00:45:09.640 --> 00:45:11.280
I give an example for myself.

00:45:11.280 --> 00:45:13.670
I had a young man come in to
do an interview a few years ago

00:45:13.670 --> 00:45:16.260
for an administrative
position at our company.

00:45:16.260 --> 00:45:18.750
And I've been a professional
musician for probably 30 years.

00:45:18.750 --> 00:45:20.050
I don't do it so much anymore,

00:45:20.050 --> 00:45:22.060
but for about 30 years
I played in bands.

00:45:22.060 --> 00:45:23.360
And so I looked at his resume

00:45:23.360 --> 00:45:25.730
and it says Berkeley School
of Music for two years.

00:45:25.730 --> 00:45:28.350
And immediately my
whole body leaned in.

00:45:28.350 --> 00:45:29.650
What do you play?

00:45:29.650 --> 00:45:30.950
What kind of music do you play?

00:45:30.950 --> 00:45:33.700
And then, you know, because I
happened to catch it this time.

00:45:33.700 --> 00:45:36.110
Like I said, I missed it
with the guy in the airplane.

00:45:36.110 --> 00:45:37.420
But this time, I happened
to catch it.

00:45:37.420 --> 00:45:38.720
I said, "Wait a second.

00:45:38.720 --> 00:45:40.070
You're not interviewing
a bass player.

00:45:40.070 --> 00:45:41.670
You're interviewing an
administrative person."

00:45:41.670 --> 00:45:43.100
So I actually said to
him, "You know what?

00:45:43.100 --> 00:45:44.620
Let's hold off on that
conversation for now.

00:45:44.620 --> 00:45:47.270
Maybe we'll talk about
that after the interview."

00:45:47.270 --> 00:45:49.140
Come back to do the interview.

00:45:49.140 --> 00:45:50.930
Now I'm not saying it would
have been perfect necessarily.

00:45:50.930 --> 00:45:52.320
That it still might
not have influenced me

00:45:52.320 --> 00:45:55.270
but I had a far greater chance than
what would have normally happened

00:45:55.270 --> 00:45:57.890
if I was unconscious, which is I
would have spent 45 minutes talking

00:45:57.890 --> 00:45:59.640
with him about music and
then I would have said,

00:45:59.640 --> 00:46:02.130
"Now let me ask you these
questions so that I can hire you."

00:46:02.130 --> 00:46:05.790
[Laughter] Because I already
heard his bass playing behind my

00:46:05.790 --> 00:46:07.090
guitar [laughter].

00:46:07.090 --> 00:46:08.810
The second, in order to do that,

00:46:08.810 --> 00:46:11.000
we have to develop the
capacity to observe ourselves.

00:46:11.000 --> 00:46:13.970
The metaphor that I like to use is
to put a flashlight on ourselves.

00:46:13.970 --> 00:46:16.470
To watch ourselves in action.

00:46:16.470 --> 00:46:18.270
Mostly the way we relate
to the world is we look

00:46:18.270 --> 00:46:21.030
at what's going on out there.

00:46:21.030 --> 00:46:22.670
And we figure out why we're --

00:46:22.670 --> 00:46:24.570
why the thing out there
is causing us trouble.

00:46:24.570 --> 00:46:26.100
We have very little
attention on what --

00:46:26.100 --> 00:46:28.150
how are we responding
to what's up there?

00:46:28.150 --> 00:46:29.450
What is that triggering in us?

00:46:29.450 --> 00:46:31.140
Who is that person reminding us of?

00:46:31.140 --> 00:46:33.260
Are there certain circumstances
where we notice

00:46:33.260 --> 00:46:36.200
that we get charged
more than others?

00:46:36.200 --> 00:46:39.750
Now that's where we begin to see
ourselves in action and that's

00:46:39.750 --> 00:46:42.740
where we begin to shift
ourselves in action.

00:46:42.740 --> 00:46:45.810 position:56%
Now my wife, one morning says to me,

00:46:45.810 --> 00:46:47.110
"Would you mind taking
out the trash?"

00:46:47.110 --> 00:46:48.420
Now I have no problem
taking out the trash.

00:46:48.420 --> 00:46:50.870
I even do it myself
sometimes, you know.

00:46:50.870 --> 00:46:53.460
But for some reason,
I just got irritated

00:46:53.460 --> 00:46:56.650
and I didn't even know why,
you know, at the moment.

00:46:56.650 --> 00:46:57.950
And then I stopped for a second.

00:46:57.950 --> 00:46:59.250
I looked and I said,
"Why am I irritated?"

00:46:59.250 --> 00:47:00.550
And then I realized.

00:47:00.550 --> 00:47:04.970
At that moment I saw -- I was seven
years old and she was my mother.

00:47:04.970 --> 00:47:07.780
My mother and I used to have
righteous battles over the trash.

00:47:07.780 --> 00:47:09.640
Some of you remember those
kinds of things or have them

00:47:09.640 --> 00:47:10.940
with your own children, right?

00:47:10.940 --> 00:47:15.220
And at that moment, something about
the way she said it or something

00:47:15.220 --> 00:47:18.030
about that circumstance reminded
me of my mother giving me stuff

00:47:18.030 --> 00:47:19.830
about not taking out the trash.

00:47:19.830 --> 00:47:21.130
And so I left.

00:47:21.130 --> 00:47:22.430
I said, "Sure, Mom.

00:47:22.430 --> 00:47:23.730
I'll take it out."

00:47:23.730 --> 00:47:25.030
And given that we -- we
both do this work together.

00:47:25.030 --> 00:47:26.710
She knew exactly what I meant and
laughed and that was the end of it.

00:47:26.710 --> 00:47:28.670
There's something liberating
about this.

00:47:28.670 --> 00:47:30.790
In order to do this, the
third thing is we have

00:47:30.790 --> 00:47:33.630
to practice what I call
constructive uncertainty.

00:47:33.630 --> 00:47:36.970
Turn some of our exclamation
points into question marks.

00:47:36.970 --> 00:47:41.920
Is that person really that way or
might I be seeing them that way?

00:47:44.140 --> 00:47:45.970
That's a huge distinction.

00:47:45.970 --> 00:47:49.760
And one of the ways we do this
is by slowing ourselves down.

00:47:49.760 --> 00:47:51.060
The breath is really valuable.

00:47:51.060 --> 00:47:53.020
I've been working with
police officers around this.

00:47:53.020 --> 00:47:56.080
And one of the things I'm
teaching them is to use the breath

00:47:56.080 --> 00:47:58.120
when they're on to
emergent crime scenes.

00:47:58.120 --> 00:48:00.360
If you just simply do
some deep breathing,

00:48:00.360 --> 00:48:02.850
it slows down the process
a little bit.

00:48:02.850 --> 00:48:05.450
It doesn't put them -- so I'm
not talking about just sitting

00:48:05.450 --> 00:48:08.880
in cross positions saying
"Om," or anything like that.

00:48:08.880 --> 00:48:11.480
I'm just talking about -- the
reason it happens, by the way,

00:48:11.480 --> 00:48:13.180
there's a physiological
reason for this.

00:48:13.180 --> 00:48:16.940
That the part of your brain
that you need to use in order

00:48:16.940 --> 00:48:18.870
to consciously slow
down your breathing,

00:48:18.870 --> 00:48:21.420 position:56%
to deepen your breathing -- when you
say, "Okay, take a deeper breath,"

00:48:21.420 --> 00:48:23.550
is your prefrontal cortex.

00:48:23.550 --> 00:48:26.040
You go out of your limbic
system when you do that

00:48:26.040 --> 00:48:29.190
and your prefrontal area
now is what's in charge.

00:48:29.190 --> 00:48:32.260
The prefrontal area is the
slower part of your brain.

00:48:32.260 --> 00:48:36.790 position:56%
They may get to the emergent crime
scene and for a split second longer,

00:48:36.790 --> 00:48:39.160
wait before they pull that trigger.

00:48:39.160 --> 00:48:42.590
For a split second longer,
consider what they're doing.

00:48:42.590 --> 00:48:45.180
Because you know, I have tremendous
-- I want to make it really clear,

00:48:45.180 --> 00:48:46.480
I have tremendous compassion

00:48:46.480 --> 00:48:48.020
for what police officers
have to deal with as well.

00:48:48.020 --> 00:48:50.450
You put yourself in the situation
where in moments you have

00:48:50.450 --> 00:48:52.940
to make a decision like to
cost somebody else their life.

00:48:52.940 --> 00:48:54.980
It could cost you your career.

00:48:54.980 --> 00:48:57.590 position:56%
You could be the next public pariah.

00:48:57.590 --> 00:49:00.270
And yet, if you wait too
long, you could be killed.

00:49:00.270 --> 00:49:04.570 position:56%
I mean, I don't know anybody here
but I'm not signing up for that job.

00:49:04.570 --> 00:49:08.060
But at the same time, we know the
consequences of it not going well.

00:49:08.060 --> 00:49:09.770
So we're trying to
teach people to be able

00:49:09.770 --> 00:49:11.070
to be more conscious about that.

00:49:11.070 --> 00:49:13.380
Rollo May, a great psychologist
said, "Freedom is the capacity

00:49:13.380 --> 00:49:15.980
to pause between stimulus
and response."

00:49:15.980 --> 00:49:18.750
Another one that we found that
really makes a difference is

00:49:18.750 --> 00:49:22.280
to engage with others and expose
yourself to counter stereotypes.

00:49:22.280 --> 00:49:24.220
In other words, positive
examples of people

00:49:24.220 --> 00:49:26.530
who normally have negative
stereotypes around.

00:49:26.530 --> 00:49:28.680
So pictures on the
wall make a difference.

00:49:28.680 --> 00:49:31.800
Things like Black History
Month still matter

00:49:31.800 --> 00:49:34.760
because they give us
positive stereotypes.

00:49:34.760 --> 00:49:36.140
Now it would be a lot better

00:49:36.140 --> 00:49:39.620
if the other 11 months were White
History Month and if we didn't,

00:49:39.620 --> 00:49:44.310
you know -- if we didn't
continually reinforce that,

00:49:44.310 --> 00:49:45.930
if we really embedded it more.

00:49:45.930 --> 00:49:47.980
But nonetheless, these kinds
of things really matter

00:49:47.980 --> 00:49:50.120
because they give us
those counter stereotypes.

00:49:50.120 --> 00:49:52.660
Spending time with
people makes a difference.

00:49:52.660 --> 00:49:56.290
Meeting people from other cultures,
identities, races, racial groups,

00:49:56.290 --> 00:49:58.040
sexual orientation
makes the difference.

00:49:58.040 --> 00:49:59.690
You know, in a sad way, you know,

00:49:59.690 --> 00:50:02.470
one of the things we're
finding that's in the research

00:50:02.470 --> 00:50:05.680
that behind the acceleration
of rights

00:50:05.680 --> 00:50:11.540
for LGBT people today
ironically was the AIDS epidemic.

00:50:11.540 --> 00:50:13.980
Because what did the
AIDS epidemic do?

00:50:13.980 --> 00:50:16.780
It made it obvious that certain
people who people loved too

00:50:16.780 --> 00:50:18.970
in their family, all of a sudden,

00:50:18.970 --> 00:50:21.290
their sexual orientation
became more apparent.

00:50:21.290 --> 00:50:25.630
We never knew Rock Hudson
was gay until he got AIDS.

00:50:25.630 --> 00:50:27.760
That's not to suggest, by the
way, that all people have AIDS.

00:50:27.760 --> 00:50:29.060
We know that they're not.

00:50:29.060 --> 00:50:31.500
But the point is in the early
days, that it had that impact.

00:50:31.500 --> 00:50:34.440
Now, for one thing to not
like those gay people,

00:50:34.440 --> 00:50:37.460
it's another thing entirely
to not like my son Bobby,

00:50:37.460 --> 00:50:42.340
or my cousin Johnny, or
my sister-in-law Sally.

00:50:42.340 --> 00:50:44.190
When it becomes personal,
it's very different.

00:50:44.190 --> 00:50:48.280
And then the last one is to
establish ways to get feedback,

00:50:48.280 --> 00:50:51.030
to create relationships so people
can come up to us and say, "Look,

00:50:51.030 --> 00:50:52.520
you may not have intended
anything about this

00:50:52.520 --> 00:50:54.460
but let me tell you how
your behavior affected me."

00:50:54.460 --> 00:50:57.440
Now for those of us who are in
power in leadership positions,

00:50:57.440 --> 00:50:59.520
it's critically important
that we recognize that we have

00:50:59.520 --> 00:51:00.910
to set the tone for that.

00:51:00.910 --> 00:51:03.070
We have to be the ones who put
ourselves out there and be open

00:51:03.070 --> 00:51:06.840
to feedback because otherwise
people project all of their --

00:51:06.840 --> 00:51:08.700
you know, authority
figures from their lives.

00:51:08.700 --> 00:51:11.350
If you had a father who didn't
like feedback from you --

00:51:11.350 --> 00:51:14.490
or very few fathers do, I
find, you know [laughter].

00:51:14.490 --> 00:51:18.060
I'm speaking as somebody with
four children [laughter].

00:51:18.060 --> 00:51:20.760
Then you may be hesitant
even if the boss says, "Sure,

00:51:20.760 --> 00:51:23.250
tell me what you're thinking,"
because what we tack on to the end

00:51:23.250 --> 00:51:26.180
of that sentence is even if it
costs you your job, you know.

00:51:26.180 --> 00:51:28.320
But creating a flow back and forth

00:51:28.320 --> 00:51:31.140
where we can give each other
feedback actually creates a way

00:51:31.140 --> 00:51:33.420
for us to see ourselves
in other people's eyes.

00:51:33.420 --> 00:51:36.340
And it could be incredibly
valuable in this process.

00:51:36.340 --> 00:51:39.620
Now I want to spend just the last
minute or two talking about systems

00:51:39.620 --> 00:51:41.760
because you're working in
an organization and we know

00:51:41.760 --> 00:51:43.060
that we can change systems.

00:51:43.060 --> 00:51:45.000
In 1970, 5% of the musicians

00:51:45.000 --> 00:51:47.200
in the major orchestras
in the world were women.

00:51:47.200 --> 00:51:49.210
In 1980, there was only 12.

00:51:49.210 --> 00:51:51.470
Still only 12% even after 15 years

00:51:51.470 --> 00:51:56.020
of modern women's movement
-- the resurgence of it.

00:51:56.020 --> 00:51:57.570
The number is now over 40%.

00:51:57.570 --> 00:51:58.870
What happened?

00:51:58.870 --> 00:52:02.420
They put in a whole range
of structures and systems

00:52:02.420 --> 00:52:04.540
that changed the way
they did auditions.

00:52:04.540 --> 00:52:07.800
The first one was they began to
advertise for auditions rather

00:52:07.800 --> 00:52:09.300
than simply to invite
people to them.

00:52:09.300 --> 00:52:12.430
It used to be the conductor would
say, "Get the second chair violin

00:52:12.430 --> 00:52:14.750
for Philadelphia to
come and audition."

00:52:14.750 --> 00:52:17.550
Now what they do is ask or
advertise them in trade magazines

00:52:17.550 --> 00:52:19.550
so people can show up and audition.

00:52:19.550 --> 00:52:20.940
The second thing they
did is they started

00:52:20.940 --> 00:52:22.820
to use panels rather
than individuals.

00:52:22.820 --> 00:52:25.140
The conductor used to make
the choice individually.

00:52:25.140 --> 00:52:27.490
Now what they do is they
have panels of people

00:52:27.490 --> 00:52:29.080
so that you have different
points of view

00:52:29.080 --> 00:52:30.610
and the more diverse
the panel, the better.

00:52:30.610 --> 00:52:33.200
So you can get different
points of view, you know,

00:52:33.200 --> 00:52:35.700
what did we think rather
than what did I think?

00:52:35.700 --> 00:52:37.380
And the most important
thing they did was

00:52:37.380 --> 00:52:40.090
that they changed the fundamental
structure of the audition itself.

00:52:40.090 --> 00:52:44.090
They began to have people
audition behind screens and walking

00:52:44.090 --> 00:52:47.760
out on rugs so that people could
no longer see the musician.

00:52:47.760 --> 00:52:51.270
They could no longer hear
the shoes of the musician.

00:52:51.270 --> 00:52:52.830
All they could hear was the music.

00:52:52.830 --> 00:52:54.320
This was, by the way, for
those of you who are fans.

00:52:54.320 --> 00:52:58.140
This is where <i>The
Voice </i>came from on TV.

00:52:58.140 --> 00:53:00.650
And what they found was it
fundamentally changed the way

00:53:00.650 --> 00:53:01.950
to music.

00:53:01.950 --> 00:53:03.250
So when you're changing a system,

00:53:03.250 --> 00:53:04.550
it's not enough just
to do individual work.

00:53:04.550 --> 00:53:07.320
Yes, we want to look at education
because education is important.

00:53:07.320 --> 00:53:08.900
And we're not talking about
a quick talk like this.

00:53:08.900 --> 00:53:11.570
I'm talking about actually spending
some time understanding these

00:53:11.570 --> 00:53:14.170
dynamics and how we
respond to these dynamics.

00:53:14.170 --> 00:53:16.820
The second is to create
priming techniques because even

00:53:16.820 --> 00:53:18.870
if you have the best
training program in the world,

00:53:18.870 --> 00:53:21.210
if you don't do a performance
review until four months from now,

00:53:21.210 --> 00:53:22.640
how much are you going to remember?

00:53:22.640 --> 00:53:25.110
So you might have a
little tool that you use.

00:53:25.110 --> 00:53:26.870
We call them performance
support tools.

00:53:26.870 --> 00:53:29.170
Before I do a performance
review, I take two minutes

00:53:29.170 --> 00:53:31.670
to watch this little video clip
or I read this sheet of paper.

00:53:31.670 --> 00:53:35.140 position:56%
I answer these questions so that I'm
reminded to pay attention to some

00:53:35.140 --> 00:53:37.220
of the dynamics that might show
up in the performance review.

00:53:37.220 --> 00:53:40.320
It makes a huge difference.

00:53:40.320 --> 00:53:41.620
The third -- whoops.

00:53:41.620 --> 00:53:43.810
The third one is to change some
of our systems and structures

00:53:43.810 --> 00:53:45.720
like do we interview
people in the same way?

00:53:45.720 --> 00:53:47.020
Maybe we will shift
that a little bit.

00:53:47.020 --> 00:53:51.010
Maybe we have panel interviews
rather than individual interviews.

00:53:51.010 --> 00:53:53.510
Maybe we send the interview
questions out to people a couple

00:53:53.510 --> 00:53:56.670
of days early because that balances
out English as a second language

00:53:56.670 --> 00:53:58.990 position:56%
or introversion versus extroversion.

00:53:58.990 --> 00:54:01.090
You know, maybe we'd be sure
that we interview people

00:54:01.090 --> 00:54:02.460
on all the same circumstances

00:54:02.460 --> 00:54:04.250
because you interview
one person fresh

00:54:04.250 --> 00:54:05.980
when you're nine o'clock
in your office.

00:54:05.980 --> 00:54:08.540
The second person in the cafeteria
at noon and the third person

00:54:08.540 --> 00:54:11.350
over Skype -- you're conducting
three different interviews.

00:54:11.350 --> 00:54:13.700
Now so there are things that we
can do structurally to change that.

00:54:13.700 --> 00:54:16.360
Actually for those of you who buy
the book, in the appendix there,

00:54:16.360 --> 00:54:19.240
I have 16 pages of ideas
for those kinds of things.

00:54:19.240 --> 00:54:20.540
And then finally, we need

00:54:20.540 --> 00:54:23.550
to establish a system
of accountability.

00:54:23.550 --> 00:54:26.090
We need to keep track of
these things at every stage

00:54:26.090 --> 00:54:28.800
because what we notice is
by the time we usually --

00:54:28.800 --> 00:54:32.110
for most people and most
organizations, we have one metric

00:54:32.110 --> 00:54:34.830
for diversity which
is how many are there.

00:54:34.830 --> 00:54:36.220 position:56%
But if we really look at the system,

00:54:36.220 --> 00:54:37.670
we see well how many
applied for jobs?

00:54:37.670 --> 00:54:39.270
How many were offered jobs?

00:54:39.270 --> 00:54:40.570
How many accepted jobs?

00:54:40.570 --> 00:54:42.080
Now how many are successful
after six months?

00:54:42.080 --> 00:54:45.350
We could begin to see when the
breakdown in the system happens.

00:54:45.350 --> 00:54:47.950
So there are things
we can do about this.

00:54:47.950 --> 00:54:49.250
Yes, it exists.

00:54:49.250 --> 00:54:50.780
It's inevitability for human
beings but there are things

00:54:50.780 --> 00:54:52.080
that we could do about it.

00:54:52.080 --> 00:54:53.380
And I'd like to end
with this picture.

00:54:53.380 --> 00:54:55.180
This is a picture of an
Aspen forest in Colorado,

00:54:55.180 --> 00:54:58.190
because at the essence
this is what I'm learning

00:54:58.190 --> 00:54:59.820
about who we are as human beings.

00:54:59.820 --> 00:55:01.210
You know, we look at these forests.

00:55:01.210 --> 00:55:02.850
Some of you, I'm sure, have
seen them if you travel

00:55:02.850 --> 00:55:04.150
to that part of the country.

00:55:04.150 --> 00:55:05.450
And they're majestic.

00:55:05.450 --> 00:55:06.920
Thousands of acres of these
ramrod straight trees.

00:55:06.920 --> 00:55:09.750
They go up 80 to 100
feet tall, incredible.

00:55:09.750 --> 00:55:12.170
Do you know the interesting
thing about the Aspen trees?

00:55:12.170 --> 00:55:14.070 position:56%
They're not individual trees at all.

00:55:14.070 --> 00:55:18.150
The Aspen forest has the largest
intact organisms in the world.

00:55:18.150 --> 00:55:20.700
They're connected by
common root systems.

00:55:20.700 --> 00:55:24.210
The way they grow is that one
tree [inaudible] around another

00:55:24.210 --> 00:55:25.780 position:56%
and another and another and another.

00:55:25.780 --> 00:55:29.590
The largest one in Northern
Utah has 80,000 trees.

00:55:29.590 --> 00:55:31.480
It's one plant.

00:55:31.480 --> 00:55:33.270
One plant.

00:55:33.270 --> 00:55:36.070
For me, it's a perfect metaphor
for who we are as human beings.

00:55:36.070 --> 00:55:38.310
We act like we're each
different but in reality,

00:55:38.310 --> 00:55:41.060
when we understand
our psychomechanisms,

00:55:41.060 --> 00:55:44.190
the way we think -- we're actually
more similar than we think we are.

00:55:44.190 --> 00:55:46.110
We check different material,
different life stories

00:55:46.110 --> 00:55:50.160
that we process differently
but we actually process --

00:55:50.160 --> 00:55:53.250
excuse me, different content to
process but we actually process

00:55:53.250 --> 00:55:55.060
that information very
much the same way.

00:55:55.060 --> 00:55:56.360
And if we can really get that,

00:55:56.360 --> 00:55:58.900
then instead of saying,
"Why are you that way?"

00:55:58.900 --> 00:56:02.740
We could say, "Why
are you that way?"

00:56:02.740 --> 00:56:05.210
So there's a difference
between fear and curiosity.

00:56:05.210 --> 00:56:08.240
And that conversation we
can create environments

00:56:08.240 --> 00:56:10.340
in which everybody can thrive.

00:56:10.340 --> 00:56:12.140
Thank you.

